27    /**
28    * An immutable time period specifying a set of duration field values.
29    * <p>
30    * A time period is divided into a number of fields, such as hours and seconds.
31    * Which fields are supported is defined by the PeriodType class.
32    * The default is the standard period type, which supports years, months, weeks, days,
33    * hours, minutes, seconds and millis.
34    * <p>
35    * When this time period is added to an instant, the effect is of adding each field in turn.
36    * As a result, this takes into account daylight savings time.
37    * Adding a time period of 1 day to the day before daylight savings starts will only add
38    * 23 hours rather than 24 to ensure that the time remains the same.
39    * If this is not the behaviour you want, then see {@link Duration}.
40    * <p>
41    * The definition of a period also affects the equals method. A period of 1
42    * day is not equal to a period of 24 hours, nor 1 hour equal to 60 minutes.
43    * This is because periods represent an abstracted definition of a time period
44    * (eg. a day may not actually be 24 hours, it might be 23 or 25 at daylight
45    * savings boundary). To compare the actual duration of two periods, convert
46    * both to durations using toDuration, an operation that emphasises that the
47    * result may differ according to the date you choose.
48    * <p>
49    * Period is thread-safe and immutable, provided that the PeriodType is as well.
50    * All standard PeriodType classes supplied are thread-safe and immutable.
51    *
52    * @author Brian S O'Neill
53    * @author Stephen Colebourne
54    * @see MutablePeriod
55    * @since 1.0
56    */
 
100% Uncovered Elements: 0 (403) Complexity: 118 Complexity Density: 0.45

236    /**
237    * Creates a period from two partially specified times, calculating
238    * by field difference.
239    * <p>
240    * The two partials must contain the same fields, thus you can specify
241    * two <code>LocalDate</code> objects, or two <code>LocalTime</code> objects,
242    * but not one of each. Also, the partial may not contain overlapping
243    * fields, such as dayOfWeek and dayOfMonth.
244    * <p>
245    * Calculation by field difference works by extracting the difference
246    * one field at a time and not wrapping into other fields.
247    * Thus 2005-06-09/2007-04-12 will yield P2Y-2M3D.
248    * <p>
249    * For example, you have an event that always runs from the 27th of
250    * each month to the 2nd of the next month. If you calculate this
251    * period using a standard constructor, then you will get between
252    * P3D and P6D depending on the month. If you use this method, then
253    * you will get P1M-25D. This field-difference based period can
254    * be successfully applied to each month of the year to obtain the
255    * correct end date for a given start date.
256    *
257    * @param start the start of the period, must not be null
258    * @param end the end of the period, must not be null
259    * @throws IllegalArgumentException if the partials are null or invalid
260    * @since 1.1
261    */

286    /**
287    * Creates a new empty period with the standard set of fields.
288    * <p>
289    * One way to initialise a period is as follows:
290    * <pre>
291    * Period = new Period().withYears(6).withMonths(3).withSeconds(23);
292    * </pre>
293    * Bear in mind that this creates four period instances in total, three of
294    * which are immediately discarded.
295    * The alternative is more efficient, but less readable:
296    * <pre>

300    * <pre>
301    * Period = Period.years(6).withMonths(3).withSeconds(23);
302    * </pre>

362    /**
363    * Creates a period from the given millisecond duration using the standard
364    * set of fields.
365    * <p>
366    * Only precise fields in the period type will be used.
367    * For the standard period type this is the time fields only.
368    * Thus the year, month, week and day fields will not be populated.
369    * <p>
370    * If the duration is small, less than one day, then this method will perform
371    * as you might expect and split the fields evenly.
372    * <p>
373    * If the duration is larger than one day then all the remaining duration will
374    * be stored in the largest available precise field, hours in this case.
375    * <p>
376    * For example, a duration equal to (365 + 60 + 5) days will be converted to
377    * ((365 + 60 + 5) * 24) hours by this constructor.
378    * <p>
379    * For more control over the conversion process, you have two options:
380    * <ul>
381    * <li>convert the duration to an {@link Interval}, and from there obtain the period
382    * <li>specify a period type that contains precise definitions of the day and larger
383    * fields, such as UTC
384    * </ul>
385    *
386    * @param duration the duration, in milliseconds
387    */

500    /**
501    * Creates a period between the given instants using the standard set of fields.
502    * <p>
503    * Most calculations performed by this method have obvious results.
504    * The special case is where the calculation is from a "long" month to a "short" month.
505    * Here, the result favours increasing the months field rather than the days.
506    * For example, 2013-01-31 to 2013-02-28 is treated as one whole month.
507    * By contrast, 2013-01-31 to 2013-03-30 is treated as one month and 30 days
508    * (exposed as 4 weeks and 2 days).
509    * The results are explained by considering that the start date plus the
510    * calculated period result in the end date.
511    * <p>
512    * Another special case is around daylight savings. Consider the case where there
513    * is a DST gap from 01:00 to 02:00. The period from 00:30 to 02:30 will return
514    * one hour, not two, due to the missing hour.
515    * However, once the period exceeds one day, a different effect comes into play.
516    * Consider the period from 00:30 just before the DST gap to 02:30 one day later.
517    * Since this exceeds a day, the algorithm first adds one day following normal period
518    * rules, to get 00:30 one day later, and then adds 2 hours to reach 02:30.
519    * In this way, the DST gap effectively "disappears".
520    * In other words, the addition of days takes precedence over the addition of hours.
521    *
522    * @param startInstant interval start, null means now
523    * @param endInstant interval end, null means now
524    */
 
100% Uncovered Elements: 0 (1) Complexity: 1 Complexity Density: 1
525  15 public Period(ReadableInstant startInstant, ReadableInstant endInstant) {...
526  15 super(startInstant, endInstant, null);
527    }
